# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: industrial-iot
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:industrial-iot/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The **industrial Internet of things** (**IIoT**) refers to interconnected sensors, instruments, and other devices networked together with computers' industrial applications, including manufacturing and energy management.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] This connectivity allows for data collection, exchange, and analysis, potentially facilitating improvements in productivity and efficiency as well as other economic benefits.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is an evolution of a distributed control system (DCS) that allows for a higher degree of automation by using cloud computing to refine and optimize the process controls.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The IIoT is enabled by technologies such as cybersecurity, cloud computing, edge computing, mobile technologies, machine-to-machine, 3D printing, advanced robotics, big data, Internet of things, RFID technology, and cognitive computing.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT systems are usually conceived as a layered modular architecture of digital technology.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The device layer refers to the physical components: CPS, sensors or machines.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The network layer consists of physical network buses, cloud computing and communication protocols that aggregate and transport the data to the service layer, which consists of applications that manipulate and combine data into information that can be displayed on the driver dashboard.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The top-most stratum of the stack is the content layer or the user interface.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The history of the IIoT begins with the invention of the programmable logic controller (PLC) by Richard E.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Morley in 1968, which was used by General Motors in their automatic transmission manufacturing division.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] These PLCs allowed for fine control of individual elements in the manufacturing chain.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] In 1975, Honeywell and Yokogawa introduced the world's first DCSs, the TDC 2000 and the CENTUM system, respectively.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] These DCSs were the next step in allowing flexible process control throughout a plant, with the added benefit of backup redundancies by distributing control across the entire system, eliminating a singular point of failure in a central control room.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] As early as in 1994, greater industrial applications were envisioned, as Reza Raji described the concept in IEEE Spectrum as "[moving] small packets of data to a large set of nodes, so as to integrate and automate everything from home appliances to entire factories".
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The concept of the Internet of things first became popular in 1999, through the Auto-ID Center at MIT and related market-analysis publications.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Radio-frequency identification (RFID) was seen by Kevin Ashton (one of the founders of the original Auto-ID Center) as a prerequisite for the Internet of things at that point.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] If all objects and people in daily life were equipped with identifiers, computers could manage and inventory them.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Besides using RFID, the tagging of things may be achieved through such technologies as near field communication, barcodes, QR codes and digital watermarking.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the first consequences of implementing the industrial internet of things (by equipping objects with minuscule identifying devices or machine-readable identifiers) would be to create instant and ceaseless inventory control.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Another benefit of implementing an IIoT system is the ability to create a digital twin of the system.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Using this digital twin allows for further optimization of the system by allowing for experimentation with new data from the cloud without having to halt production or sacrifice safety, as the new processes can be refined virtually until they are ready to be implemented.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] A digital twin can also serve as a training ground for new employees who won't have to worry about real impacts on the live system.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] IoT frameworks help support the interaction between "things" and allow for more complex structures like distributed computing and the development of distributed applications.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The term industrial internet of things is often encountered in the manufacturing industries, referring to the industrial subset of the IoT.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Potential benefits of the industrial internet of things include improved productivity, improved reliability, analytics and the transformation of the workplace.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The potential of growth by implementing IIoT is predicted to generate $15 trillion of global GDP by 2030.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] While connectivity and data acquisition are imperative for IIoT, they are not the end goals, but rather the foundation and path to something bigger.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Of all the technologies, predictive maintenance is an "easier” application, as it is applicable to existing assets and management systems.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Intelligent maintenance systems can reduce unexpected downtime and increase productivity, which is projected to save up to 12% over scheduled repairs, reduce overall maintenance costs up to 30%, and eliminate breakdowns up to 70%, according to some studies.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Cyber-physical systems (CPS) are the core technology of industrial big data and they will be an interface between human and the cyber world.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Integration of sensing and actuation systems connected to the Internet can optimize energy consumption as a whole.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] It is expected that IoT devices will be integrated into all forms of energy consuming devices (switches, power outlets, bulbs, televisions, etc.) and be able to communicate with the utility supply company in order to effectively balance power generation and energy usage.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Using advanced metering infrastructure (AMI) devices connected to the Internet backbone, electric utilities can not only collect data from end-user connections, but also manage other distribution automation devices like transformers and reclosers.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Using IIoT in car manufacturing implies the digitalization of all elements of production.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Software, machines, and humans are interconnected, enabling suppliers and manufacturers to rapidly respond to changing standards.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT enables efficient and cost-effective production by moving data from the customers to the company's systems, and then to individual sections of the production process.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIoT, new tools and functionalities can be included in the manufacturing process.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] For example, 3D printers simplify the way of shaping pressing tools by printing the shape directly from steel granulate.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] These tools enable new possibilities for designing (with high precision).
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Customization of vehicles is also enabled by IIoT due to the modularity and connectivity of this technology.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] While in the past they worked separately, IIoT now enables humans and robots to cooperate.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Robots take on heavy and repetitive activities, so the manufacturing cycles are quicker and the vehicle comes to the market more rapidly.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Factories can quickly identify potential maintenance issues before they lead to downtime and many of them are moving to a 24-hour production plant, due to higher security and efficiency.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The majority of automotive manufacturers companies have production plants in different countries, where different components of the same vehicle are built.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT makes it possible to connect these production plants to each other, creating the possibility to move within facilities.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Big data can be visually monitored which enables companies to respond faster to fluctuations in production and demand.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT support, large amounts of raw data can be stored and sent by the drilling gear and research stations for cloud storage and analysis.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] With IIOT technologies, the oil and gas industry has the capability to connect machines, devices, sensors, and people through interconnectivity, which can help companies better address fluctuations in demand and pricing, address cybersecurity, and minimize environmental impact.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Across the supply chain, IIOT can improve the maintenance process, the overall safety, and connectivity.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Drones can be used to detect possible oil and gas leaks at an early stage and at locations that are difficult to reach (e.g. offshore).
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] They can also be used to identify weak spots in complex networks of pipelines with built-in thermal imaging systems.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Increased connectivity (data integration and communication) can help companies with adjusting the production levels based on real-time data of inventory, storage, distribution pace, and forecasted demand.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows monitoring of pipeline threats, improving risk management, and providing situational awareness.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Benefits also apply to specific processes of the oil and gas industry.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The exploration process of oil and gas can be done more precisely with 4D models built by seismic imaging.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] These models map fluctuations in oil reserves and gas levels, they strive to point out the exact quantity of resources needed, and they forecast the lifespan of wells.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The application of smart sensors and automated drillers gives companies the opportunity to monitor and produce more efficiently.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Further, the storing process can also be improved with the implementation of IIOT by collecting and analyzing real-time data to monitor inventory levels and temperature control.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIOT can enhance the transportation process of oil and gas by implementing smart sensors and thermal detectors to give real-time geolocation data and monitor the products for safety reasons.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] These smart sensors can monitor the refinery processes, and enhance safety.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The demand for products can be forecasted more precisely and automatically be communicated to the refineries and production plants to adjust production levels.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] In the agriculture industry, IIoT helps farmers to make decisions about when to harvest.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Sensors collect data about soil and weather conditions and propose schedules for fertilizing and irrigating.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Some livestock farms implant microchips into animals.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] This allows the farmers not only to trace their animals, but also pull up information about the lineage, weight, or health.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The integration of IIoT data in the photovoltaic (PV) industry can significantly enhance the efficiency, reliability, and performance of solar power systems.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] IIoT with AI data can be utilized for real-time monitoring, performance optimization, fault detection, diagnostics.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] As the IIoT expands, new security concerns arise with it.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Every new device or component that connects to the IIoT can become a potential liability.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Gartner estimates that by 2020, more than 25% of recognized attacks on enterprises will involve IoT-connected systems, despite accounting for less than 10% of IT security budgets.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Existing cybersecurity measures are vastly inferior for Internet-connected devices compared to their traditional computer counterparts, which can allow for them to be hijacked for DDoS-based attacks by botnets like Mirai.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Another possibility is the infection of Internet-connected industrial controllers, like in the case of Stuxnet, without the need for physical access to the system to spread the worm.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Additionally, IIoT-enabled devices can allow for more “traditional” forms of cybercrime, as in the case of the 2013 Target data breach, where information was stolen after hackers gained access to Target's networks via credentials stolen from a third party HVAC vendor.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] The pharmaceutical manufacturing industry has been slow to adopt IIoT advances because of security concerns such as these.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] One of the difficulties in providing security solutions in IIoT applications is the fragmented nature of the hardware.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Consequently, security architectures are turning towards designs that are software-based or device-agnostic.
[src:industrial-iot/industrial-internet-of-things] Hardware-based approaches, like the use of data diodes, are often used when connecting critical infrastructure.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The **Fourth Industrial Revolution**, also known as **4IR**, **Industry 4.0** or the **Intelligence Age**, is a neologism describing rapid technological advancement in the 21st century.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It follows the Third Industrial Revolution (the "Information Age").
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The term was popularized in 2016 by Klaus Schwab, the World Economic Forum founder and former executive chairman, who asserts that these developments represent a significant shift in industrial capitalism.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] A part of this phase of industrial change is the joining of technologies like artificial intelligence, gene editing, to advanced robotics that blur the lines between the physical, digital, and biological worlds.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] This integration results in increasing automation, improving communication and self-monitoring, and the use of smart machines that can analyse and diagnose issues without the need for human intervention.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It also represents a social, political, and economic shift from the digital age of the late 1990s and early 2000s to an era of embedded connectivity distinguished by the ubiquity of technology in society that changes the ways humans experience and know the world around them.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It posits that we have created and are entering an augmented social reality compared to just the natural senses and industrial ability of humans alone.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Fourth Industrial Revolution is sometimes expected to mark the beginning of an *imagination age*, where creativity and imagination become the primary drivers of economic value.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The phrase *Fourth Industrial Revolution* was first introduced by a team of scientists developing a high-tech strategy for the German government.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Klaus Schwab, former executive chairman of the World Economic Forum (WEF), introduced the phrase to a wider audience in a 2015 article published by *Foreign Affairs*.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] "Mastering the Fourth Industrial Revolution" was the 2016 theme of the World Economic Forum Annual Meeting, in Davos-Klosters, Switzerland.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] On 10 October 2016, the Forum announced the opening of its Centre for the Fourth Industrial Revolution in San Francisco.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] This was also subject and title of Schwab's 2016 book.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Schwab includes in this fourth era technologies that combine hardware, software, and biology (cyber-physical systems), and emphasizes advances in communication and connectivity.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In *The Great Reset* proposal by the WEF, *The Fourth Industrial Revolution* is included as a strategic intelligence in the solution to rebuild the economy sustainably following the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The First Industrial Revolution was marked by a transition from hand production methods to machines through the use of steam power and water power.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The implementation of new technologies took a long time, so the period which this refers to was between 1760 and 1820, or 1840 in Europe and the United States.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Its effects had consequences on textile manufacturing, which was first to adopt such changes, as well as iron industry, agriculture, and mining–although it also had societal effects with an ever stronger middle class.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Second Industrial Revolution, also known as the Technological Revolution, is the period between 1871 and 1914 that resulted from installations of extensive railroad and telegraph networks, which allowed for faster transfer of people and ideas, as well as electricity.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Increasing electrification allowed for factories to develop the modern production line.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Third Industrial Revolution, also known as the Digital Revolution, began in the late 20th century.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It is characterized by the shift to an economy centered on information technology, marked by the advent of personal computers, the Internet, and the widespread digitalization of communication and industrial processes.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] A book by Jeremy Rifkin titled *The Third Industrial Revolution*, published in 2011, focused on the intersection of digital communications technology and renewable energy.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It was made into a 2017 documentary by Vice Media.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In essence, the Fourth Industrial Revolution is the trend towards automation and data exchange in manufacturing technologies and processes which include cyber-physical systems (CPS), internet of things (IoT), cloud computing, cognitive computing, and artificial intelligence.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Machines improve human efficiency in performing repetitive functions, and the combination of machine learning and computing power allows machines to carry out increasingly complex tasks.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It also emphasizes decentralized decisions – the ability of cyber physical systems to make decisions on their own and to perform their tasks as autonomously as possible.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Only in the case of exceptions, interference, or conflicting goals, are tasks delegated to a higher level.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Proponents of the Fourth Industrial Revolution suggest it is a distinct revolution rather than simply a prolongation of the Third Industrial Revolution.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Critics of the concept dismiss Industry 4.0 as a marketing strategy.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] They suggest that although revolutionary changes are identifiable in distinct sectors, there is no systemic change so far.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In addition, the pace of recognition of Industry 4.0 and policy transition varies across countries; the definition of Industry 4.0 is not harmonised.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] One of the most known figures is Jeremy Rifkin who "agree[s] that digitalization is the hallmark and defining technology in what has become known as the Third Industrial Revolution".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] However, he argues "that the evolution of digitalization has barely begun to run its course and that its new configuration in the form of the Internet of Things represents the next stage of its development".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 networks a wide range of new technologies to create value.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Using cyber-physical systems that monitor physical processes, a virtual copy of the physical world can be designed.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Characteristics of cyber-physical systems include the ability to make decentralised decisions independently, reaching a high degree of autonomy.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The value created in Industry 4.0 can be relied upon in electronic identification, in which the smart manufacturing requires set technologies to be incorporated in the manufacturing process to thus be classified as in the development path of Industry 4.0 and no longer digitisation.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Fourth Industrial Revolution fosters "smart factories", which are production environments where facilities and logistics systems are organised with minimal human intervention.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The technical foundations on which smart factories are based are cyber-physical systems that communicate with each other using IoT.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] An important part of this process is the exchange of data between the product and the production line.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] This enables more efficient supply chain connectivity and better organisation within a production environment.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Within modular structured smart factories, cyber-physical systems monitor physical processes, create a virtual copy of the physical world, and make decentralised decisions.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Over the internet of things, cyber-physical systems communicate and cooperate with each other and with humans in synchronic time both internally and across organizational services offered and used by participants of the value chain.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Artificial intelligence (AI) has a wide range of applications across all sectors of the economy.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It gained prominence following advancements in deep learning during the 2010s, and its impact intensified in the 2020s with the rise of generative AI, a period often referred to as the "AI boom".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Models like GPT-4o can engage in verbal and textual discussions and analyse images.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] AI is a key driver of Industry 4.0, orchestrating technologies like robotics, automated vehicles, and real-time data analytics.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] By enabling machines to perform complex tasks, AI is redefining production processes and reducing changeover times.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] AI could also significantly accelerate, or even automate software development.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Some experts believe that AI alone could be as transformative as an industrial revolution.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Multiple companies such as OpenAI and Meta have expressed the goal of creating artificial general intelligence (AI that can do virtually any cognitive task a human can), making large investments in data centres and GPUs to train more capable AI models.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Humanoid robots have traditionally lacked usefulness.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] They had difficulty picking simple objects due to imprecise control and coordination, and they wouldn't understand their environment and how physics works.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] They were often explicitly programmed to do narrow tasks, failing when encountering new situations.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Modern humanoid robots, however, are typically based on machine learning, and in particular reinforcement learning.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In 2024, humanoid robots are rapidly becoming more flexible, easier to train, and versatile.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 facilitates predictive maintenance, due to the use of advanced technologies, including IoT sensors.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Predictive maintenance, which can identify potential maintenance issues in real time, allows machine owners to perform cost-effective maintenance before the machinery fails or gets damaged.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] For example, a company in Los Angeles could understand if a piece of equipment in Singapore is running at an abnormal speed or temperature.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] They could then decide whether or not it needs to be repaired.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Fourth Industrial Revolution is said to have extensive dependency on 3D printing technology.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Some advantages of 3D printing for industry are that 3D printing can print many geometric structures, as well as simplify the product design process.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It is also relatively environmentally friendly.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In low-volume production, it can also decrease lead times and total production costs.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Moreover, it can increase flexibility, reduce warehousing costs and help the company towards the adoption of a mass customisation business strategy.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In addition, 3D printing can be very useful for printing spare parts and installing it locally, therefore reducing supplier dependence and reducing the supply lead time.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Sensors and instrumentation drive the central forces of innovation, not only for Industry 4.0 but also for other "smart" megatrends, such as smart production, smart mobility, smart homes, smart cities, and smart factories.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Smart sensors are devices which generate the data and allow further functionality from self-monitoring and self-configuration to condition monitoring of complex processes.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] With the capability of wireless communication, they reduce installation effort to a great extent and help realise a dense array of sensors.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] However, there are a few issues, such as time synchronisation error, data loss, and dealing with large amounts of harvested data, which all limit the implementation of full-fledged systems.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Moreover, additional limits on these functionalities represent the battery power.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Smart sensors in these two fields are still in the testing stage.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] These connected sensors collect, interpret and communicate the information available in the plots (leaf area, vegetation index, chlorophyll, hygrometry, temperature, water potential, radiation).
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Based on this scientific data, the objective is to enable real-time monitoring via a smartphone with a range of advice that optimises plot management in terms of results, time and costs.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] On the farm, these sensors can be used to detect crop stages and recommend inputs and treatments at the right time, as well as controlling the level of irrigation.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The food industry requires more and more security and transparency and full documentation is required.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] This new technology is used as a tracking system as well as the collection of human data and product data.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Knowledge economy is an economic system in which production and services are largely based on knowledge-intensive activities that contribute to an accelerated pace of technical and scientific advance, as well as rapid obsolescence.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 aids transitions into knowledge economy by increasing reliance on intellectual capabilities rather than on physical inputs or natural resources.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Many countries have set up institutional mechanisms to foster the adoption of Industry 4.0 technologies.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Australia has a Digital Transformation Agency (est.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] 2015) and the Prime Minister's Industry 4.0 Taskforce (est.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] 2016), which promotes collaboration with industry groups in Germany and the USA.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Brazil's embrace of Industry 4.0 technologies has been a slow and inconsistent process.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Initial assessments clearly indicated a considerable gap in digital preparedness among the nation's industrial businesses.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] A significant survey, conducted by the National Confederation of Industry, revealed concerning statistics: 42% of Brazilian companies were completely unaware of how crucial digital technologies are for industrial competitiveness.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Furthermore, a substantial 46% either weren't utilizing these technologies or were unsure about their application.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] These findings collectively underscored a widespread lack of awareness and readiness for digital transformation across the Brazilian industrial landscape.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The term "Industrie 4.0" was publicly introduced in the same year at the Hannover Fair.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] German professor Wolfgang Wahlster is sometimes called the inventor of the "Industry 4.0" term.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In October 2012, the Working Group on Industry 4.0 presented a set of Industry 4.0 implementation recommendations to the German federal government.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The workgroup members and partners are recognised as the founding fathers and driving force behind Industry 4.0.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] On 8 April 2013 at the Hannover Fair, the final report of the Working Group Industry 4.0 was presented.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] This working group was headed by Siegfried Dais, of Robert Bosch GmbH, and Henning Kagermann, of the German Academy of Science and Engineering.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] As Industry 4.0 principles have been applied by companies, they have sometimes been rebranded.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] For example, the aerospace parts manufacturer Meggitt PLC has branded its own Industry 4.0 research project M4.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In Germany, the impact of the shift to Industry 4.0 (and especially digitisation) on the labour market has been discussed under the heading "Work 4.0".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The federal government in Germany is a leader in the development of the I4.0 policy through its ministries of the German federal Ministry of Education and Research (BMBF) and BMWi.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Through the publishing of set objectives and goals for enterprises to achieve, the German federal government attempts to set the direction of the digital transformation.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] However, there is a gap between German enterprise's collaboration and knowledge of these set policies.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The biggest challenge SMEs in Germany are currently facing regarding digital transformation of their manufacturing processes is ensuring that there is a concrete IT and application landscape to support further digital transformation efforts.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The characteristics of the German government's Industry 4.0 strategy involve the strong customisation of products under the conditions of highly flexible (mass-) production.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The required automation technology is improved by the introduction of methods of self-optimization, self-configuration, self-diagnosis, cognition and intelligent support of workers in their increasingly complex work.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The largest project in Industry 4.0 as of July 2013 is the BMBF leading-edge cluster "Intelligent Technical Systems Ostwestfalen-Lippe (its OWL)".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Another major project is the BMBF project RES-COM, as well as the Cluster of Excellence "Integrative Production Technology for High-Wage Countries".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In 2015, the European Commission started the international Horizon 2020 research project CREMA (cloud-based rapid elastic manufacturing) as a major initiative to foster the Industry 4.0 topic.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In Estonia, the digital transformation dubbed as the 4th Industrial Revolution by Klaus Schwab and the World Economic Forum in 2015 started with the restoration of independence in 1991.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Although a latecomer to the information revolution due to 50 years of Soviet occupation, Estonia leapfrogged to the digital era, while skipping the analogue connections almost completely.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The early decisions made by Prime Minister Mart Laar on the course of the country's economic development led to the establishment of what is today known as e-Estonia, one of the worlds most digitally advanced nations.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Another example is the Indonesian initiative Making Indonesia 4.0, which focuses on improving industrial performance.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] India, with its expanding economy and extensive manufacturing sector, has embraced the digital revolution, leading to significant advancements in manufacturing.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Indian program for Industry 4.0 centres around leveraging technology to produce globally competitive products at cost-effective rates while adopting the latest technological advancements of Industry 4.0.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Society 5.0 envisions a society that prioritizes the well-being of its citizens, striking a harmonious balance between economic progress and the effective addressing of societal challenges through a closely interconnected system of both the digital realm and the physical world.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] This concept was introduced in 2019 in the 5th Science and Technology Basic Plan for Japanese Government as a blueprint for a forthcoming societal framework.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Malaysia's national policy on Industry 4.0 is known as Industry4WRD.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Launched in 2018, key initiatives in this policy include enhancing digital infrastructure, equipping the workforce with 4IR skills, and fostering innovation and technology adoption across industries.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] South Africa appointed a Presidential Commission on the Fourth Industrial Revolution in 2019, consisting of about 30 stakeholders with a background in academia, industry and government.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] South Africa has also established an Inter ministerial Committee on Industry 4.0.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] A nationwide survey of 577 lecturers in Technical Engineering at 52 TVET college campuses across South Africa found that 52.3% of participants were unaware of technological advancements in their area of specialization and their potential impact on technical training.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] These findings indicate that South African TVET lecturers have limited awareness of the technological advancements needed to participate effectively in the 4IR era.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Accordingly, South African Minister of Higher Education, Blade Nzimande, placed the upskilling of TVET lecturers' 4IR-related skills high on the ministry's agenda.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Republic of Korea has had a Presidential Committee on the Fourth Industrial Revolution since 2017.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Republic of Korea's I-Korea strategy (2017) is focusing on new growth engines that include AI, drones, and autonomous cars, in line with the government's innovation-driven economic policy.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In a policy paper published in 2019, the UK's Department for Business, Energy & Industrial Strategy, titled "Regulation for the Fourth Industrial Revolution", outlined the need to evolve current regulatory models to remain competitive in evolving technological and social settings.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The Department of Homeland Security in 2019 published a paper called 'The Industrial Internet of things (IIOT): Opportunities, Risks, Mitigation'.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The base pieces of critical infrastructure are increasingly digitised for greater connectivity and optimisation.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Hence, its implementation, growth and maintenance must be carefully planned and safeguarded.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The paper discusses not only applications of IIOT but also the associated risks.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] It has suggested some key areas where risk mitigation is possible.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] To increase coordination between the public, private, law enforcement, academia and other stakeholders the DHS formed the National Cybersecurity and Communications Integration Center (NCCIC).
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The aerospace industry has sometimes been characterised as "too low volume for extensive automation".
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] However, Industry 4.0 principles have been investigated by several aerospace companies, and technologies have been developed to improve productivity where the upfront cost of automation cannot be justified.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] One example of this is the aerospace parts manufacturer Meggitt PLC's M4 project.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] The increasing use of the industrial internet of things is referred to as Industry 4.0 at Bosch, and generally in Germany.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Industry 4.0 inspired Innovation 4.0, a move toward digitisation for academia and research and development.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] In 2017, the £81M Materials Innovation Factory (MIF) at the University of Liverpool opened as a centre for computer aided materials science, where robotic formulation, data capture, and modelling are being integrated into development practices.
[src:industrial-iot/industry-4-0] Industry 5.0 has been proposed as a strategy to create a paradigm shift for an industrial landscape in which the primary focus should no longer be on increasing efficiency, but rather on promoting the well-being of society and sustainability of the economy and industrial production.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Andy Stanford-Clark (IBM) and Arlen Nipper (then working for Eurotech, Inc.) authored the first version of the protocol in 1999.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] It was used to monitor oil pipelines within the SCADA industrial control system.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The goal was to have a protocol that is bandwidth-efficient, lightweight and uses little battery power, because the devices were connected via satellite link, which was extremely expensive at that time.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Historically, the "MQ" in "MQTT" came from the IBM MQ (then "MQSeries") product line, where it stands for "Message Queue".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] However, the protocol provides publish-and-subscribe messaging (no queues, in spite of the name).
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] In the specification opened by IBM, as version 3.1, the protocol was referred to as "MQ Telemetry Transport".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Subsequent versions released by OASIS strictly refer to the protocol as just "MQTT", although the technical committee itself is named "OASIS Message Queuing Telemetry Transport Technical Committee".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Since 2013, "MQTT" does not stand for anything.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] In 2013, IBM submitted MQTT v3.1 to the OASIS specification body with a charter that ensured only minor changes to the specification could be accepted.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] After taking over maintenance of the standard from IBM, OASIS released version 3.1.1 on October 29, 2014.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] A more substantial upgrade to MQTT version 5, adding several new features, was released on March 7, 2019.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT-SN (MQTT for Sensor Networks) is a variation of the main protocol aimed at battery-powered embedded devices on non-TCP/IP networks.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Any network that provides for bidirectional transport may be used (such as UDP and serial links), though Zigbee is the original design target.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Communication within a MQTT-SN network as well as to the outside MQTT network is coordinated by a "MQTT-SN Gateway".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The MQTT protocol defines two types of network entities: a message broker and a number of clients.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] An MQTT broker is a server that receives messages from publishing clients and then routes the messages to the appropriate destination clients.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] An MQTT client is any device (from a microcontroller up to a full-fledged server) that runs an MQTT library and connects to an MQTT broker over a network.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Information is organized in a hierarchy of topics.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] When a publisher has a new item of data to distribute, it sends a control message with the data to the connected broker.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The broker then distributes the information to any clients that have subscribed to that topic.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The publisher does not need to have any data on the number or locations of subscribers; and subscribers, in turn, do not have to be configured with any data about the publishers.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] If a broker receives a message on a topic for which there are no current subscribers, the broker discards the message unless the publisher of the message designated the message as a retained message.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] A retained message is a normal MQTT message with the retained flag set to true.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The broker stores the last retained message and the corresponding quality of service (QoS) for the selected topic.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Each client that subscribes to a topic pattern that matches the topic of the retained message receives the retained message immediately after they subscribe.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The broker stores only one retained message per topic.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This allows new subscribers to a topic to receive the most current value rather than waiting for the next update from a publisher.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] When a publishing client first connects to the broker, it can set up a default message to be sent to subscribers if the broker detects that the publishing client has unexpectedly disconnected from the broker.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Clients only interact with a broker, but a system may contain several broker servers that exchange data based on their current subscribers' topics.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] A minimal MQTT control message can be as little as two bytes of data.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] A control message can carry nearly 256 megabytes of data if needed.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] There are 14 defined message types used to connect and disconnect a client from a broker, to publish data, to acknowledge receipt of data, and to supervise the connection between client and server.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT relies on the TCP protocol for data transmission.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] A variant, MQTT-SN, is used over other transports such as UDP or Bluetooth.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT sends connection credentials in plain text format and does not include any measures for security or authentication.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This can be provided by using TLS to encrypt and protect the transferred information against interception, modification or forgery.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The default unencrypted MQTT port is 1883.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The MQTT broker is a piece of software running on a computer (running on-premises or in the cloud), and could be self-built or hosted by a third party.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] It is available in both open source and proprietary implementations.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT clients do not use a direct connection address of the intended recipient, but use the subject line called "Topic".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Anyone who subscribes receives a copy of all messages for that topic.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Multiple clients can subscribe to a topic from a single broker (one to many capability), and a single client can register subscriptions to topics with multiple brokers (many to one).
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Each client can both produce and receive data by both publishing and subscribing, i.e. the devices can publish sensor data and still be able to receive the configuration information or control commands (MQTT is a bi-directional communication protocol).
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This helps in both sharing data, managing and controlling devices.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] A client cannot broadcast the same data to a range of topics, and must publish multiple messages to the broker, each with a single topic given.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] With the MQTT broker architecture, the client devices and server application become decoupled.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] In this way, the clients are kept unaware of each other's information.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT, if configured to, can use TLS encryption with certificate, username and password protected connections.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Optionally, the connection may require certification, in the form of a certificate file that a client provides and must match with the server's copy.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] In case of failure, the broker software and clients can automatically hand over to a redundant/automatic backup broker.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Backup brokers can also be set up to share the load of clients across multiple servers on site, in the cloud, or a combination of these.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The broker can support both standard MQTT and MQTT for compliant specifications such as Sparkplug.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This can be done with the same server, at the same time and with the same levels of security.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The broker keeps track of all the session's information as the device goes on and off, in a function called "persistent sessions".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] In this state, a broker will store both connection info for each client, topics each client has subscribed to, and any messages for a topic with a QoS of 1 or 2.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Ability to easily scale from a single device to thousands.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Management and tracking of client connection states, including security credentials and certificates (when appropriately configured).
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Reduction of strain on cellular or satellite networks without compromising security (when appropriately configured).
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Waits for a connection to be established with the server and creates a link between the nodes.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Waits for the MQTT client to finish any work it must do, and for the TCP/IP session to disconnect.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Returns immediately to the application thread after passing the request to the MQTT client.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] In 2019, OASIS released the official MQTT 5.0 standard.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Each connection to the broker can specify a QoS measure.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This field does not affect handling of the underlying TCP data transmissions; it is only used between MQTT senders and receivers.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT protocol version 3.1.1 requires the server (broker) to use a timeout that is one-and-a-half times the keepalive value specified by the client.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This (and similar keepalive functionalities in other protocols such as HTTP) enables a slow DoS attack published in 2020 called SlowITe, in which the attacker tries to open and maintain as many connections as possible, depriving legitimate users of their connections.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] New variations of the attack and new detection/mitigation methods are topics of current research.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT clustering is a technique employed to ensure high availability, fault tolerance, and scalability in MQTT deployments.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] As an efficient and lightweight messaging protocol, MQTT clustering allows for the creation of a resilient network of interconnected broker nodes, ensuring continuous and reliable message delivery even in the face of hardware failures or network disruptions.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] MQTT does not guarantee that messages published by independent clients arrive at subscribers in the order they were generated.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The OASIS MQTT specification provides ordering guarantees only within a single client session on a single topic; events originating from separate clients or generated across independent connections may be delivered out of sequence.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This limitation is particularly consequential in IoT deployments that use MQTT lifecycle events (connect and disconnect notifications) to track device connectivity state.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Major broker implementations acknowledge this directly: Amazon Web Services states in its AWS IoT Core developer documentation that "lifecycle messages might be sent out of order" and that subscribers "might receive duplicate messages".
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] The practical consequence is that a disconnect notification generated before a reconnect notification may arrive at the subscribing application after it, causing monitoring systems that apply a last-write-wins policy to record a device as offline when it has already reconnected.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] This is a known failure mode in event-driven architectures and was characterised in the distributed systems literature as an inherent property of asynchronous message passing by Leslie Lamport in 1978.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Independent benchmarks have documented the operational cost of event ordering inversions in production IoT deployments.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Commonly applied mitigations include debounce windows (delaying action on disconnect events for a fixed interval to allow late-arriving messages to be processed), polling or re-query patterns, and application-layer sequence numbering.
[src:industrial-iot/mqtt] Each mitigation imposes trade-offs: debounce windows introduce detection latency for genuine disconnect events and may suppress legitimate notifications; polling adds network overhead and is unsuitable for passive sensors.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Although developed by the same organization, OPC UA differs significantly from its predecessor, Open Platform Communications (OPC).
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The Foundation's goal for OPC UA was to provide a path forward from the original OPC communications model (namely the Microsoft Windows-only process exchange COM/DCOM) that would better meet the emerging needs of industrial automation.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] After more than three years of specification work and another year for a prototype implementation, the first version of the Unified Architecture was released in 2006.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The current version of the specification is on 1.04 (22 November 2017).
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The new version of OPC UA now has added publish/subscribe in addition to the client/server communications infrastructure.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] These drawbacks along with a number of other considerations pushed the decision to develop a new and independent stack for OPC UA, which replaces COM/DCOM.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This communication stack reflects the beginning of various innovations.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC UA architecture is a service-oriented architecture (SOA) and is based on different logical levels.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] OPC Base Services are abstract method descriptions, which are protocol independent and provide the basis for OPC UA functionality.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The transport layer puts these methods into a protocol, which means it serializes/deserializes the data and transmits it over the network.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Two protocols are specified for this purpose.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] One is a binary TCP protocol, optimized for high performance and the second is Web service-oriented.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC information model is a Mesh Network based on nodes.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] These nodes can include any kind of meta information, and are similar to the objects of object-oriented programming (OOP).
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] A node can have attributes for read access such as DataAccess (DA), HistoricDataAccess (HDA), methods that can be called (Commands), and triggered events that can be transmitted (such as AlarmEvent (AE), DataAccess, and DataChange).
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Nodes hold process data as well as other types of metadata.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC namespace contains the type-model.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The namespace is a URI that identifies the naming authority responsible for assigning the identifier element of the NodeId.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Naming authorities include the local Server, the underlying system, standards bodies and consortia.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] It is expected that most Nodes will use the URI of the Server or of the underlying system.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Client software can verify what profiles a server supports.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This is necessary to obtain information, if a server only supports DA functionality or additionally AE, HDA, etc.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Additionally, information can be obtained about whether a server supports a given profile.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] At the OPC UA DevCon in October 2006, in Munich the first prototypes were presented live.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Various UA Servers have been shown on a Beckhoff programmable logic controller and an embedded test board from Euros.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The Beckhoff PLC is based on Windows XP Embedded and the embedded controller is based on the real-time operating system Euros.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The company Embedded Labs Ltd demonstrated an OPC UA Server based on their own C++ UA Stack executing on a single chip ARM microcontroller with 64kB RAM.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] In October 2012 the German Fraunhofer-Application Center IOSB-INA and the Institute for industrial Information Technologies (inIT) showed that an OPC UA server is scalable down to 15 kB RAM and 10 kB ROM and therefore usable at chip level.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The current version of the specification is 1.05.06, and was released on 22 October, 2025.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Additionally, part 100 Devices, and part 200 Industrial Automation are also available.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] These build on the core set of specifications, and adds new common definitions that then are used in different companion specifications.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] E.g. both *OPC UA for Analyser Devices* and *OPC UA for Machinery* builds directly on part 100.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] In contrast to the COM-based specifications, the UA specifications are not pure application specifications.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] They describe typical UA internal mechanisms, which get handled through the communication stack and are normally only of interest for those that port a stack to a specific target or those that want to implement their own UA stack.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The OPC UA application developers code against the OPC UA API and therefore mainly use API documentation.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Nevertheless, part 3, 4, and 5 may be of interest for application developers.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] OPC UA is a versatile industrial communication protocol that is designed to be transport-agnostic, and operate over several transport mechanisms, each corresponding to different layers of the OSI model.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] It can use, TCP, UDP or Ethernet directly, or it can also be encapsulated within higher-level application protocols such as HTTPS, WebSockets, AMQP, and MQTT.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The architecture of a UA application, independent of whether it is the server or client part, is structured into levels.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Some parts equalize to the former COM Proxy/Stubs and get provided by the OPC Foundation.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The portability level is new; it simplifies porting the UA ANSI C stack to other target platforms.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] A port layer for Windows and Linux is also provided by the OPC Foundation.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] UA Security consists of authentication and authorization, encryption and data integrity via signatures.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] For Web Services the WS-SecureConversation gets used and is therefore compatible with .NET and other SO–AP implementations.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] For the binary variant, the algorithms of WS-SecureConversation have been followed and also converted to a binary equivalent.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This is named as UA Secure Conversation.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] There is also a mixed version where the code is binary, but the transport layer is SOAP.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This is a compromise between efficient binary coding and firewall-friendly transmission.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Binary coding always requires UA Secure Conversation.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The authentication uses X.509 certificates exclusively.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] It relies on the application developer to choose which certificate store the UA application gets bound to.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] For instance, it is possible to use the public key infrastructure (PKI) of an Active Directory.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] UA APIs are available in several programming languages.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Commercial SDKs are available for C, C++, Java, and .NET.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Open-source stacks are available at least for C, C++, Java, JavaScript(node), Tcl and Python.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The .NET implementation uses ANSI C for the lower levels and implements the rest natively in .NET.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] That means only the handling of the socket and the Message-Chunking gets integrated from the ANSI C stack.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] De-serialization takes place directly in .NET and therefore gets converted directly into .NET structures and objects.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This provides better performance than de-serializing into a C structure first and then copying the data to a .NET structure afterwards.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Various stacks for Java were being developed.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Code directly on the network layer (similar to the current .Net implementation) and de-serialize in Java.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This saves one data copy execution, but still depends on the C stack.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] This was observed to be the most portable, but estimated to take the most engineering effort to implement.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] The Eclipse Milo project provides a pure-Java, open-source, implementation of the UA 1.05 client and server specification.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Apache PLC4X project provides pure-Java, open-source implementation of UA client as well as network level frame descriptions which can be used for cross-language implementations.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] Alternatively, there is the simple variant to only support the WebService protocol.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] For that, a SOAP Toolkit that supports WS-Security is needed.
[src:industrial-iot/opc-unified-architecture] IEC 62541 is a standard for OPC Unified Architecture.
